{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Sherlock Holmes of Baker Street | title_orig = | translator = | image = | caption = | author = [[William S. Baring-Gould]] | cover_artist = | country = [[United States]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Mystery novels]] | publisher = | release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) | pages = | isbn = | isbn_note = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Sherlock Holmes of Baker Street: A Life of the World's First Consulting Detective''''' is a 1962 novel by [[William S. Baring-Gould]]. The book purports to be a [[biography]] of [[Sherlock Holmes]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hardy|first=Phil|title=The BFI Companion to Crime|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=1997|page=168|ISBN=9780520215382}}</ref>
Some aspects of the book were loosely based on the life of Baring-Gould's paternal grandfather, [[Sabine Baring-Gould]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Redmond|first=Chistopher|title=Sherlock Holmes Handbook (Second Edition)|publisher=Dundurn|year=2009|page=180|ISBN=9781770705920}}</ref>
Five years later, Baring-Gould would go on to publish an ''Annotated Sherlock Holmes'', which would be considered definitive,<ref>{{cite web|last=Hickling|first=Alfred|title=A four-pipe poseur |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/dec/04/classics.arthurconandoyle|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 3, 2004|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name="redmond81">{{cite book|last=Redmond|first=Chistopher|title=Sherlock Holmes Handbook (Second Edition)|publisher=Dundurn|year=2009|page=81|ISBN=9781770705920}}</ref> at least until [[Leslie S. Klinger]] published ''[[The New Annotated Sherlock Holmes]]'' in 2004–2005.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weingarten|first=Marc|title=Case of the Lawyer With a Sherlock Holmes Bent|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/30/books/case-of-the-lawyer-with-a-sherlock-holmes-bent.html|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 30, 2004|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Redmond|first=Chistopher|title=Sherlock Holmes Handbook (Second Edition)|publisher=Dundurn|year=2009|page=83|ISBN=9781770705920}}</ref> Baring-Gould used many biography details he invented in ''Sherlock Holmes of Baker Street'' for his annotated volumes.<ref name="redmond81"/>
Details established by Baring-Gould, such as [[Professor Moriarty]] being Holmes' childhood tutor,<ref name="eyles">{{cite book |author=Allen Eyles |title=Sherlock Holmes: A Centenary Celebration |year=1986 |publisher=[[Harper (publisher)|Harper & Row]] |pages=105-106 |isbn=0-06-015620-1 }}</ref> that Holmes was once an actor <ref>{{cite book|last1=Greenberg|first1=Martin|last2=Lellenberg|first2=John L.|last3=Stashower|first3=Daniel|authorlink3=Daniel Stashower|title=Sherlock Holmes in America|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|year=2009|page=50|ISBN=9781602399341}}</ref>, and the continuing affair with [[Irene Adler]] leading up to the birth of a son,<ref>{{cite book|last=Redmond|first=Christopher|title=In Bed With Sherlock Holmes: Sexual Elements in Arthur Conan Doyle's Stories of the great Detective|publisher=Dundurn|year=2002|page=57|ISBN=9781770700376}}</ref> have continued to be a part of [[Sherlockian game|The Great Game]] and have been used in other [[Sherlock Holmes pastiches|Sherlockian pastiche]].<ref name="eyles"/> The book also offers one of the earliest versions of Sherlock Holmes meeting [[Jack the Ripper]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Doyle|first1=Steven|last2=Crowder|first2=David A.|title=Sherlock Holmes For Dummies|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|year=2010|page=239|ISBN=9780470484449}}</ref>
