{{other uses|Tambu (disambiguation)}}

'''''Tambu''''' (also '''''tambú''''') is a drum, music genre and dance form, found on [[Aruba]], [[Bonaire]] and [[Curaçao]], and is a major part of the [[music of Aruba and the Netherlands Antilles|Dutch Antillean music]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Xb2ibVAXO9sC&pg=PA994&dq=Garland+Encyclopedia+of+World+Music+tambu&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjN0bv66Y3TAhWlAcAKHbZ_CiAQ6AEIKTAC#v=onepage&q=Garland%20Encyclopedia%20of%20World%20Music%20tambu&f=false|title=The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music: Southeast Asia|last=Nettl|first=Bruno|last2=Miller|first2=Terry E.|last3=Stone|first3=Ruth M.|last4=Williams|first4=Sean|last5=Porter|first5=James|last6=Rice|first6=Timothy|date=1998-01-01|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=|isbn=9780824060404|location=|pages=994|language=en}}</ref> On Bonaire, it is also known as ''bari''. Curaçaoan tambu is a major part of that island's culture, and is there a genre that is considered ''muziek di zumbi'' (literally, ''spirit music'', referring to music of African origin), and is accompanied by instruments like the ''wiri'', ''agan'' and [[triangle (musical instrument)|triangle]]. The word ''tambu'' derives from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word for drum, ''tambor''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EH8ESDc9FAUC&pg=PA150&dq=tambu+aruba&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwizyPXL6Y3TAhVEBMAKHeYDDa4Q6AEIOTAF#v=onepage&q=tambu%20aruba&f=false|title=African Caribbeans: A Reference Guide|last=West|first=Alan|date=2003-01-01|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=|isbn=9780313312403|location=|pages=150|language=en}}</ref>

''Tambu'' can refer to the small drum on which the music is played, the dance that accompanies the music, or the event where the music and dance take place. In modern ''tambu'', the lyrics are usually in the [[Papiamento|Papiamento language]] and are sung along with a ''chapi'' (hoe), the ''tambu'' drum and sometimes other singers, while the audience claps to the rhythm. The ''tambu'' rhythm is complicated and is passed down orally from generation to generation. ''Tambu'' consists of two beats; ''sla habri'' and ''sla será'', the open and closed beat respectively. These beats alternate to create a musical dialogue. Additionally, there are two types of ''tambu'' music; ''telele'', which is a long, slow rising and falling melody, and ''tambu'' itself, which is faster paced and shorter in duration.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uCigiQGl1fwC&pg=PT37#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Aruba, Bonaire & Curacao Alive!|last=Brushaber|first=Susan|last2=Greenberg|first2=Arnold|date=2001-10-01|publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc|year=|isbn=9781588432599|location=|pages=242|language=en}}</ref>

